# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: building-management-system
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] BAS functionality may keep a building's climate within a specified range, provide light to rooms based on occupancy, monitor performance and device failures, and provide malfunction alarms to building maintenance staff.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] A BAS works to reduce building energy and maintenance costs compared to a non-controlled building.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Most commercial, institutional, and industrial buildings built after 2000 include a BAS, whilst older buildings may be retrofitted with a new BAS.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] A building controlled by a BAS is often referred to as an "intelligent building", a "smart building", or (if a residence) a *smart home*.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Commercial and industrial buildings have historically relied on robust proven protocols (like BACnet) while proprietary protocols (like X-10) were used in homes.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] With the advent of wireless sensor networks and the Internet of Things, an increasing number of smart buildings are resorting to using low-power wireless communication technologies such as Zigbee, Bluetooth Low Energy and LoRa to interconnect the local sensors, actuators and processing devices.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Almost all multi-story green buildings are designed to accommodate a BAS for the energy, air and water conservation characteristics.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Electrical device demand response is a typical function of a BAS, as is the more sophisticated ventilation and humidity monitoring required of "tight" insulated buildings.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Most green buildings also use as many low-power DC devices as possible.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Even a passivhaus design intended to consume no net energy whatsoever will typically require a BAS to manage heat capture, shading and venting, and scheduling device use.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Building management systems are most commonly implemented in large projects with extensive mechanical, HVAC, and electrical systems.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Systems linked to a BMS typically represent 40% of a building's energy usage; if lighting is included, this number approaches to 70%.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] BMS systems are a critical component to managing energy demand.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Improperly configured BMS systems are believed to account for 20% of building energy usage, or approximately 8% of total energy usage in the United States.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] In addition to controlling the building's internal environment, BMS systems are sometimes linked to access control (turnstiles and access doors controlling who is allowed access and egress to the building) or other security systems such as closed-circuit television (CCTV) and motion detectors.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Fire alarm systems and elevators are also sometimes linked to a BMS for monitoring.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] In case a fire is detected then only the fire alarm panel could close dampers in the ventilation system to stop smoke spreading, shut down air handlers, start smoke evacuation fans, and send all the elevators to the ground floor and park them to prevent people from using them.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Building management systems have also included disaster-response mechanisms (such as base isolation) to save structures from earthquakes.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] In more recent times, companies and governments have been working to find similar solutions for flood zones and coastal areas at-risk to rising sea levels.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Self-adjusting floating environment draws from existing technologies used to float concrete bridges and runways such as Washington's SR 520 and Japan's Mega-Float.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Analog inputs are used to read a variable measurement.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Examples are temperature, humidity and pressure sensors which could be thermistor, 4–20 mA, 0–10 volt or platinum resistance thermometer (resistance temperature detector), or wireless sensors.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] A digital input indicates a device is on or off.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Some examples of digital inputs would be a door contact switch, a current switch, an air flow switch, or a voltage-free relay contact (dry contact).
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Digital inputs could also be pulse inputs counting the pulses over a period of time.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] An example is a turbine flow meter transmitting flow data as a frequency of pulses to an input.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Nonintrusive load monitoring is software relying on digital sensors and algorithms to discover appliance or other loads from electrical or magnetic characteristics of the circuit.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] It is however detecting the event by an analog means.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] These are extremely cost-effective in operation and useful not only for identification but to detect start-up transients, line or equipment faults, etc.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Occupancy sensors detect the presence, number, and sometimes location of people in a space to enable demand-controlled systems for lighting, HVAC, and energy management.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Traditional examples include passive infrared (PIR), ultrasonic, and CO2-based detectors, but advanced systems use low-resolution thermal imaging or area sensors to provide zone-level accuracy without capturing identifiable images, ensuring privacy compliance (e.g., GDPR).
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] These sensors output analog heat signatures or digital counts that integrate with building management systems via protocols like BACnet or wireless IoT networks, reducing energy use by up to 40% through precise ventilation and lighting control.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Analog outputs control the speed or position of a device, such as a variable frequency drive, an I-P (current to pneumatics) transducer, or a valve or damper actuator.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] An example is a hot water valve opening up 25% to maintain a setpoint.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Another example is a variable frequency drive ramping up a motor slowly to avoid a hard start.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Digital outputs are used to open and close relays and switches as well as drive a load upon command.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] An example would be to turn on the parking lot lights when a photocell indicates it is dark outside.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Another example would be to open a valve by allowing 24VDC/AC to pass through the output powering the valve.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Analog outputs could also be pulse type outputs emitting a frequency of pulses over a given period of time.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] An example is an energy meter calculating kWh and emitting a frequency of pulses accordingly.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Controllers are essentially small, purpose-built computers with input and output capabilities.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] These controllers come in a range of sizes and capabilities to control devices commonly found in buildings, and to control sub-networks of controllers.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Inputs allow a controller to read temperature, humidity, pressure, current flow, air flow, and other essential factors.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] The outputs allow the controller to send command and control signals to slave devices, and to other parts of the system.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Inputs and outputs can be either digital or analog.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Digital outputs are also sometimes called discrete depending on manufacturer.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Controllers used for building automation can be grouped in three categories: programmable logic controllers (PLCs), system/network controllers, and terminal unit controllers.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] However an additional device can also exist in order to integrate third-party systems (e.g. a stand-alone AC system) into a central building automation system.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Terminal unit controllers usually are suited for control of lighting and/or simpler devices such as a package rooftop unit, heat pump, VAV box, fan coil, etc.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] The installer typically selects one of the available pre-programmed personalities best suited to the device to be controlled, and does not have to create new control logic.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Occupancy is one of two or more operating modes for a building automation system; unoccupied, morning warmup, and night-time setback are other common modes.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Occupancy is usually based on time of day schedules.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] In occupancy mode, the BAS aims to provides a comfortable climate and adequate lighting, often with zone-based control so that users on one side of a building have a different thermostat (or a different system, or sub system) than users on the opposite side.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] A temperature sensor in the zone provides feedback to the controller, so it can deliver heating or cooling as needed.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] If enabled, morning warmup (MWU) mode occurs prior to occupancy.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] During morning warmup the BAS tries to bring the building to setpoint just in time for occupancy.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] The BAS often factors in outdoor conditions and historical experience to optimize MWU.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] This is also referred to as *optimized start*.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Some buildings rely on occupancy sensors to activate lighting or climate conditioning.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Given the potential for long lead times before a space becomes sufficiently cool or warm, climate conditioning is not often initiated directly by an occupancy sensor.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Lighting can be turned on, off, or dimmed with a building automation or lighting control system based on time of day, or on occupancy sensor, photosensors and timers.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] One typical example is to turn the lights in a space on for a half-hour since the last motion was sensed.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] A photocell placed outside a building can sense darkness, and the time of day, and modulate lights in outer offices and the parking lot.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Lighting is also a good candidate for demand response, with many control systems providing the ability to dim (or turn off) lights to take advantage of DR incentives and savings.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] In newer buildings, the lighting control can be based on the field bus Digital Addressable Lighting Interface (DALI).
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Lamps with DALI ballasts are fully dimmable.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] DALI can also detect lamp and ballast failures on DALI luminaires and signals failures.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Shading and glazing are essential components in the building system, they affect occupants' visual, acoustical, and thermal comfort and provide the occupant with a view outdoor.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Automated shading and glazing systems are solutions for controlling solar heat gains and glare.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] It refers to the use of technology to control external or internal shading devices (such as blinds, and shades) or glazing itself.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] The system has an active and rapid response to various changing outdoor data (such as solar, wind) and to changing interior environment (such as temperature, illuminance, and occupant demands).
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Building shading and glazing systems can contribute to thermal and lighting improvement from both energy conservation and comfort point of view.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Dynamic shading devices allow the control of daylight and solar energy to enter into built environment in relation to outdoor conditions, daylighting demands and solar positions.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] The common products include venetian blinds, roller shades, louvers, and shutters.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] They are mostly installed on the interior side of the glazing system because of the low maintenance cost, but also can be used on the exterior or a combination of both.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Most air handlers mix return and outside air so less temperature/humidity conditioning is needed.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] This can save money by using less chilled or heated water (not all AHUs use chilled or hot water circuits).
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Some external air is needed to keep the building's air healthy.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] To optimize energy efficiency while maintaining healthy indoor air quality (IAQ), demand control (or controlled) ventilation (DCV) adjusts the amount of outside air based on measured levels of occupancy.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Analog or digital temperature sensors may be placed in the space or room, the return and supply air ducts, and sometimes the external air.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Actuators are placed on the hot and chilled water valves, the outside air and return air dampers.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] The supply fan (and return if applicable) is started and stopped based on either time of day, temperatures, building pressures or a combination.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] All modern building automation systems have alarm capabilities.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] It does little good to detect a potentially hazardous or costly situation if no one who can solve the problem is notified.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Notification can be through a computer (email or text message), pager, cellular phone voice call, audible alarm, or all of these.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] For insurance and liability purposes all systems keep logs of who was notified, when and how.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Alarms may immediately notify someone or only notify when alarms build to some threshold of seriousness or urgency.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] At sites with several buildings, momentary power failures can cause hundreds or thousands of alarms from equipment that has shut down – these should be suppressed and recognized as symptoms of a larger failure.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Some sites are programmed so that critical alarms are automatically re-sent at varying intervals.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] For example, a repeating critical alarm (of an uninterruptible power supply in 'bypass') might resound at 10 minutes, 30 minutes, and every 2 to 4 hours thereafter until the alarms are resolved.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Security systems can be interlocked to a building automation system.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] If occupancy sensors are present, they can also be used as burglar alarms.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Because security systems are often deliberately sabotaged, at least some detectors or cameras should have battery backup and wireless connectivity and the ability to trigger alarms when disconnected.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Modern systems typically use power-over-Ethernet (which can operate a pan-tilt-zoom camera and other devices up to 30–90 watts) which is capable of charging such batteries and keeps wireless networks free for genuinely wireless applications, such as backup communication in outage.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Fire alarm panels and their related smoke alarm systems are usually hard-wired to override building automation.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] For example: if the smoke alarm is activated, all the outside air dampers close to prevent air coming into the building, and an exhaust system can isolate the blaze.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Similarly, electrical fault detection systems can turn entire circuits off, regardless of the number of alarms this triggers or persons this distresses.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Fossil fuel combustion devices also tend to have their own over-rides, such as natural gas feed lines that turn off when slow pressure drops are detected (indicating a leak), or when excess methane is detected in the building's air supply.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] ASHRAE's open protocol BACnet or the open protocol LonTalk specify how most such devices interoperate.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Modern systems use SNMP to track events, building on decades of history with SNMP-based protocols in the computer networking world.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Physical connectivity between devices was historically provided by dedicated optical fiber, ethernet, ARCNET, RS-232, RS-485 or a low-bandwidth special purpose wireless network.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Modern systems rely on standards-based multi-protocol heterogeneous networking such as that specified in the IEEE 1905.1 standard and verified by the nVoy auditing mark.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Proprietary hardware dominates the controller market.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Each company has controllers for specific applications.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Some are designed with limited controls and no interoperability, such as simple packaged roof top units for HVAC.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Software will typically not integrate well with packages from other vendors.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Cooperation is at the Zigbee/BACnet/LonTalk level only.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Current systems provide interoperability at the application level, allowing users to mix-and-match devices from different manufacturers, and to provide integration with other compatible building control systems.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] These typically rely on SNMP, long used for this same purpose to integrate diverse computer networking devices into one coherent network.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] With the growing spectrum of capabilities and connections to the Internet of Things, building automation systems were repeatedly reported to be vulnerable, allowing hackers and cybercriminals to attack their components.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Buildings can be exploited by hackers to measure or change their environment: sensors allow surveillance (e.g. monitoring movements of employees or habits of inhabitants) while actuators allow to perform actions in buildings (e.g. opening doors or windows for intruders).
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] Several vendors and committees started to improve the security features in their products and standards, including KNX, Zigbee and BACnet (see recent standards or standard drafts).
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] However, researchers report several open problems in building automation security.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] On November 11, 2019, a 132-page security research paper was released titled "I Own Your Building (Management System)" by Gjoko Krstic and Sipke Mellema that addressed more than 100 vulnerabilities affecting various BMS and access control solutions by various vendors.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] On November 24, 2025, a 161-page security research paper was released titled "Project Brainfog: Beyond the Facade - Exposing Smart Giants" by Gjoko Krstic that addressed more than 1000 vulnerabilities affecting two widely used BAS controllers by ABB Group.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] It is common for room automation systems to employ a touchscreen as the primary way of controlling each operation.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] On November 27, 2018, a 29-page research paper titled "A Scalable Room Occupancy Prediction with Transferable Time Series Decomposition of CO2 Sensor Data" was published by Irvan Bastian Arief, Margaret Hamilton, and Flora Salim.
[src:building-management-system/building-automation] The paper introduced a novel approach to leveraging carbon dioxide (CO2) sensor data to predict room occupancy—enabling smarter building automation by estimating the number of occupants in a room at any given time.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] Central controllers and most terminal unit controllers are programmable, meaning the direct digital control program code may be customized for the intended use.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] The program features include time schedules, setpoints, controllers, logic, timers, trend logs, and alarms.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] The unit controllers typically have analog and digital inputs, that allow measurement of the variable (temperature, humidity, or pressure) and analog and digital outputs for control of the medium (hot/cold water and/or steam).
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] Digital inputs are typically (dry) contacts from a control device, and analog inputs are typically a voltage or current measurement from a variable (temperature, humidity, velocity, or pressure) sensing device.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] Digital outputs are typically relay contacts used to start and stop equipment, and analog outputs are typically voltage or current signals to control the movement of the medium (air/water/steam) control devices.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] An early example of a direct digital control system was completed by the Australian business Midac in 1981-1982 using R-Tec Australian designed hardware.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] The system installed at the University of Melbourne used a serial communications network, connecting campus buildings back to a control room "front end" system in the basement of the Old Geology building.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] Each remote or Satellite Intelligence Unit (SIU) ran 2 Z80 microprocessors whilst the front end ran eleven Z80's in a Parallel Processing configuration with paged common memory.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] The z80 microprocessors shared the load by passing tasks to each other via the common memory and the communications network.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] This was possibly the first successful implementation of a distributed processing direct digital control.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] When direct digital controllers are networked together they can share information through a data bus.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] The control system may speak 'proprietary' or 'open protocol' language to communicate on the data bus.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] Examples of open protocol language are Building Automation Control Network (BACnet), LonWorks (Echelon), Modbus TCP and KNX.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] When different direct digital control data networks are linked together they can be controlled from a shared platform.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] This platform can then share information from one language to another.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] For example, a LON controller could share a temperature value with a BACnet controller.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] The integration platform can not only make information shareable, but can interact with all the devices.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] Most of the integration platforms are either a PC or a network appliance.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] In many cases, the HMI (human machine interface) or SCADA (Supervisory Control And Data Acquisition) are part of it.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] Integration platform examples, to name only a few, are the Tridium Niagara AX, Trend Controls, TAC Vista, CAN2GO and the Unified Architecture i.e.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] OPC (Open Connectivity) server technology used when direct connectivity is not possible.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] Direct digital control is often used to control heating, ventilating, and air conditioning devices such as valves via microprocessors using software to perform the control logic.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] Such systems receive analog and digital inputs from the sensors and devices and, according to the control logic, provide analog or digital outputs.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] These systems may be mated with a software package that graphically allows operators to monitor, control, alarm and diagnose building equipment remotely.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] Direct digital control can be applied to optimize plant growth in a growth chamber.
[src:building-management-system/direct-digital-control] Using an algorithm based on optimal control theory, it is possible to control the speed of an induction motor using a microcontroller.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] The scope of facilities management varies by organization and sector, but commonly includes building operations and maintenance (for example mechanical, electrical and plumbing systems), space and workplace planning, and workplace services such as cleaning, security and catering.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] International standards for facilities management include the ISO 41000 series, such as ISO 41001 (a management system standard for facility management) and ISO 41011 (which defines key terminology).
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] ISO 41001:2018 specifies requirements for a facility management management system.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] The concept of facilities management originated in the 1960s, primarily in the context of IT systems management.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] The term was coined by IBM alumnus and Electronic Data Systems founder Ross Perot, to describe the integration of network management and support services.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Over time, it expanded to include broader elements of building and operational management.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Facility management as integral to the processes of strategic organizational planning was represented during a 1979 conference sponsored by Herman Miller.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Following the meeting, the furniture manufacturer opened the Facility Management Institute (FMI), with its headquarters in Ann Arbor, Michigan.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] The National Facility Management Association (NFMA) was formed in 1980, separating the overall profession from a single enterprise.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] In 1986, the first professional FM organization was launched in the UK, as the Association of Facility Managers (AFM).
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] The terms *facility management* and *facilities management* are often used interchangeably.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] ISO/TR 41013:2017 provides additional context on the scope, key concepts and benefits of facility management and the use of ISO 41011 terminology.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Professional guidance notes that organizations vary in what they include within the facilities function.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] In some cases, it includes real estate oversight or project work in addition to service delivery and workplace operations.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] **Soft FM**, referring to services supporting occupants including cleaning, catering, security, and event setups.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] According to the IFMA: "FM is the practice of coordinating the physical workplace with the people and work of the organization.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] FM may also cover activities other than business services: these are referred to as non-core functions and vary from one business sector to another.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] FM is also subject to continuous innovation and development, under pressure to reduce costs and to add value to the core business of public or private sector client organizations.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Facility management is supported with education, training, and professional qualifications often coordinated by FM institutes, universities, and associations.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Degree programs exist at both undergraduate and post-graduate levels.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Facility Management has been a recognised academic discipline since the 1990s.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Initial FM research work in Europe started in universities in the UK, the Netherlands and the Nordic countries, where academies funded research centers and began to establish courses at Bachelors, Masters, and PhD levels.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Early European FM research centers include the Centre for Facilities Management (CFM), founded in Glasgow in 1990; the Centre for People and Buildings at Delft University of Technology; and Metamorphose at the Norwegian University of Science and Technology.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] The University of Moratuwa Faculty of Architecture in Sri Lanka has offered a BSc. degree in Facilities Management since 2006.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] In 2018, 50 universities and research institutions were represented in EUROFM.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] The German Facility Management Association (GEFMA) has certified 16 FM study programs and courses at universities and universities of applied sciences in Germany.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] As of 2021, IFMA accredits university degree programs in the United States, Sri Lanka, South Korea, Singapore, Germany, Sweden, Hong Kong, Ireland, and the Netherlands.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] A facilities manager is the practitioner responsible for delivering facilities management within an organization, including coordinating building operations, maintenance and workplace services, either directly or through external providers.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] In practice, the role spans strategic planning (aligning facilities and services with organizational needs) and day-to-day operations (ensuring safe, reliable building performance and service delivery).
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Facilities managers may be employed directly by an organization or work for external service providers, depending on how facilities services are sourced and delivered.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] A core responsibility of facilities management is supporting compliance with legal and regulatory obligations related to the built environment, including occupational health and safety, building regulations, access control and fire regulations, and managing related risks.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Fire safety responsibilities often include organizing inspection, testing and maintenance of fire protection and life safety systems and maintaining required records where applicable.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Security responsibilities commonly include maintaining physical security measures such as access control systems and surveillance hardware; staffing models for guarding may be managed separately depending on the organization.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Facilities managers oversee building operations and maintenance to keep facilities safe, reliable and fit for purpose.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] This can include planned preventive maintenance, reactive repairs, statutory inspections and performance monitoring of building services such as HVAC, electrical and plumbing systems.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Many organizations plan, schedule and document maintenance and service delivery using digital systems such as computerized maintenance management systems (CMMS) or computer-aided facility management (CAFM) platforms.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Facilities managers may also coordinate workplace services that support occupants and daily operations.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Depending on the organization, this can include cleaning, grounds maintenance, waste management, catering, reception and security services, which are often outsourced or delivered via mixed in-house and contracted arrangements.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Many facilities organizations use a service desk or help desk as a single point of contact for building issues and service requests.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Requests are typically triaged and prioritized, then routed to in-house staff or contracted providers for resolution and tracking.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Facilities managers often contribute to emergency preparedness, incident response and recovery, and business continuity planning related to the built environment and critical building systems.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Space allocation, workplace standards and moves, adds and changes are common facilities functions, particularly in office and campus environments.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] This work may involve coordinating layouts, accommodating growth or reconfiguration, and ensuring that workplaces meet relevant requirements such as fire safety, accessibility, ventilation, lighting and welfare facilities.
[src:building-management-system/facility-management] Since 2009, Global FM has sponsored a "World FM Day". to celebrate and recognize the contributions of facilities management professionals.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] The first HVAC controllers utilized pneumatic controls since engineers understood fluid control.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] Thus, the properties of steam and air were used to control the flow of heated or cooled air via mechanically controlled logic.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] After the control of air flow and temperature was standardized, the use of electromechanical relays in ladder logic to switch dampers became standardized.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] Eventually, the relays became electronic switches, as transistors eventually could handle greater current loads.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] By 1985, pneumatic controls could no longer compete with this new technology although pneumatic control systems (sometimes decades old) are still common in many older buildings.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] By the year 2000, computerized controllers were common.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] Today, some of these controllers can even be accessed by web browsers, which need no longer be in the same building as the HVAC equipment.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] This allows some economies of scale, as a single operations center can easily monitor multiple buildings.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] Prior to about the late 1960s, HVAC systems were controlled by pneumatics (using air pressure and tubes to move valves and dampers).
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] Then, digital computerization began to replace those systems.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] Central controllers and most terminal unit controllers are programmable, meaning the direct digital control (DDC) program code may be customized for the intended use.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] The program features include time schedules, set points, controllers, logic, timers, trend logs, and alarms.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] The unit controllers typically have analog and digital inputs that allow measurement of the variable (temperature, humidity, or pressure) and analog and digital outputs for control of the transport medium (hot/cold water and/or steam).
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] Digital outputs are typically relay contacts used to start and stop equipment, and analog outputs are typically voltage or current signals to control the movement of the medium (air/water/steam) control devices such as valves, dampers, and motors.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] Groups of DDC controllers, networked or not, form a layer of systems themselves.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] This "subsystem" is vital to the performance and basic operation of the overall HVAC system.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] The DDC system is the "brain" of the HVAC system.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] It dictates the position of every damper and valve in a system.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] It determines which fans, pumps, and chiller run and at what speed or capacity.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] With this configurable intelligence in this "brain", we are moving to the concept of building automation.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] More complex HVAC systems can interface with a Building Automation System (BAS) to allow the building owners to have more control over the heating or cooling units.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] The building owner can monitor the system and respond to alarms generated by the system from local or remote locations.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] The system can be scheduled for occupancy or the configuration can be changed from the BAS.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] Sometimes the BAS is directly controlling the HVAC components.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] Depending on the BAS different interfaces can be used.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] Today, there are also dedicated gateways that connect advanced VRV / VRF and Split HVAC Systems with Home Automation and BMS (Building Management Systems) controllers for centralized control and monitoring, obviating the need to purchase more complex and expensive HVAC systems.
[src:building-management-system/hvac-control-system] In addition, such gateway solutions are capable of providing remote control operation of all HVAC indoor units over the internet.
